The elections saw a tough fight between the Indian National Congress (INC) and the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP). The Janata Dal (Secular) (JD-S) also emerged as a key player in the elections. In the final results, no single party managed to secure a clear majority of 113 seats in the 224-member assembly. The BJP emerged as the single largest party with 104 seats, while the INC won 78 seats and the JD-S won 37 seats. The remaining seats were won by independent candidates and smaller parties. Despite emerging as the largest party, the BJP was unable to form a government on its own. In a dramatic turn of events, the JD-S and the INC formed a post-poll alliance and staked claim to form the government with the support of independent candidates. The Governor of Karnataka invited the BJP to form the government first, but it resigned shortly after failing to secure a majority in a trust vote. Ultimately, the JD-S and INC coalition formed the government with H.D. Kumaraswamy of the JD-S becoming the Chief Minister of Karnataka. The BJP, on the other hand, became the principal opposition party in the state. Overall, the Karnataka State Assembly Elections 2018 were a closely contested affair with multiple political parties vying for power. While the BJP emerged as the single largest party, it was ultimately unable to form a government on its own.
